{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13901"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.39,0.27,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102587"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1939"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102587"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department during the wet season in far north Queensland with a week\u0027s history of fevers, a productive cough with purulent sputum, and worsening shortness of breath. He describes a change from clear-white coloured sputum, which is normal for him, to a thick, green sputum of increasing quantity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and COPD, for which he takes metformin and beclometasone/formoterol/glycopyrronium (Trimbow). He admits to significant alcohol intake, drinking six standard drinks every night, and is a continuing smoker (10 cigarettes per day, for a 20-year pack history). He is up to date with his vaccines, including influenza, COVID-19, and pneumococcal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and is febrile. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Coarse crackles are appreciable on auscultation. He is orientated to person, place and time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Intravenous meropenem","Oral doxycycline","Intravenous vancomycin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question is advanced for a medical student.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s presentation with severe community-acquired pneumonia in far north Queensland during the wet season, along with his significant risk factors, the most appropriate initial antibiotic treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous meropenem\u003C/strong\u003E. This is due to the high risk of melioidosis, caused by \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E. Meropenem is a broad-spectrum carbapenem antibiotic that covers most gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, including \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E, and extended-spectrum beta-lactamase (ESBL) producing organisms. It should be noted that ceftazidime 2 g (child: 50 mg/kg up to 2 g) intravenously can also be used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E is a gram-negative environmental bacterium and opportunistic human pathogen. It is the causative agent of melioidosis, which most commonly presents as pneumonia but may also manifest as abscesses or cutaneous ulcers. Melioidosis is an important consideration in northern Australia, particularly during the wet season when extreme weather events can increase its incidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for melioidosis include immunosuppression, diabetes, chronic kidney disease, chronic lung disease, and hazardous alcohol use - all of which this patient has. Long-term corticosteroid use, as seen in this patient\u0027s COPD treatment, is also a risk factor. The bacteria is endemic to water and soil in northern Australia, with increased exposure during the wet season.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for severe pneumonia and does not cover \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E. It is typically used for mild community-acquired pneumonia in low-risk patients. Amoxicillin is effective against many gram-positive bacteria (including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E) and some gram-negative bacteria, but it lacks coverage for atypical pathogens and \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used for community-acquired pneumonia but does not provide adequate coverage for \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E. It would be insufficient in this high-risk scenario. Ceftriaxone is a third-generation cephalosporin with good coverage against many gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, but it is not effective against \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for atypical pneumonia but would be inadequate for severe pneumonia and does not provide reliable coverage for melioidosis. Doxycycline is effective against atypical pathogens like \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, as well as some gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, but it is not a first-line choice for severe pneumonia or melioidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is used for suspected methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) pneumonia but would not be appropriate as initial therapy in this case as it does not cover gram-negative organisms including \u003Cem\u003EB. pseudomallei\u003C/em\u003E. Vancomycin is primarily effective against gram-positive bacteria, including MRSA and penicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, but has no activity against gram-negative pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmpirical treatment for severe community-acquired pneumonia in tropical regions during the wet season should include coverage for melioidosis. Intravenous meropenem is the first-line treatment in this scenario. It\u0027s often combined with intravenous azithromycin to cover atypical pathogens. The patient should be admitted to hospital for close monitoring and supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intravenous meropenem is the first-line treatment for severe community-acquired pneumonia in northern Australia during the wet season due to the risk of melioidosis.","B. pseudomallei is an important cause of pneumonia to consider in those living in northern Australia, particularly if the patient has underlying immunosuppression.","Risk factors for melioidosis include diabetes, chronic respiratory disease, chronic kidney disease, and hazardous alcohol use."],"references":["Melioidosis. Queensland Health. Updated August 2023. Accessed July 12, 2024. https://www.health.qld.gov.au/cdcg/index/melioidosis","Melioidosis. In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed July 12, 2024. Updated April 2019. https://www-tg-org-au.elibrary.jcu.edu.au","Community-acquired pneumonia in adults. In: Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed July 12, 2024. Updated June 2023. https://www-tg-org-au.elibrary.jcu.edu.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-13T08:37:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T08:41:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6520"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102587"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmono